<h2>Portfolio</h2>
<p><b>Welcome to my <u>Portfolio</u>!</b></p> 
<p>As an educator, student, and lifelong learner, I am constantly seeking opportunities to grow both personally and professionally. This portfolio represents a collection of projects, experiences, and accomplishments that reflect my commitment to continuous learning, creativity, and professional development. Whether through teaching, literary analysis, research, or basic digital design, I enjoy challenging myself to explore new ideas and develop new skills. Each artifact included here demonstrates not only what I have learned, but also how I continue to evolve as both a scholar and an educator.</p>
<hr>
<p><img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/55350613528_f8e34447ce_z.jpg" alt="Today's Agenda for Act 1 - Scene 4 and 5 for Romeo and Juliet"></p>
<p>This is one of the lessons that I had conducted for Freshmen when we were exploring Shakespeare's <i>Romeo and Juliet</i>. To ensure that students understood sonnets and their structures, I challenged students to write their own prior to performing it for their class as a group. Students were engaged, and it had become one of the most engaged lessons for this unit. Since Shakespeare is written in a way that can make learning it difficult, as a teacher, I took the time to go over some of the more confusing yet common words that they would encounter. </p>
<hr>
<p><img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/55349523427_723bf6a478_z.jpg" alt="Today's Agenda for Chapter 6 of Night and more historical context"></p>
<p>During the course of the year, students were tasked with reading the memoir, <i>Night</i>. This was a memoir that I had read as a freshmen in high school, and I had a chance to revisit the text with my students. The instruction that I wished my teacher had done during that time for me (as a student), I was able to do this for my students this year. To drive the point home, we (as a class) went through more historical context, and we watched the documentary - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9LZkU_O7vrs">Violins of Hope</a>. In addition to the lessons, I also had students do mini-research projects on some of notable people from World War II history. Many students said that it made them understand the historic context a little bit more, and with them needing to do oral presentations within their groups - it showed off their hard work more. 
